11:46.500 --> 11:48.900
You know about the Vietnam War.

11:48.933 --> 11:52.667
What you might not know is that
while that conflict raged on,

11:52.700 --> 11:56.367
Oman, along with an elite force
of British special operators

11:56.400 --> 11:59.400
and military advisors,
was engaged in a war

11:59.433 --> 12:01.700
in the country's southern
Dhofar region

12:01.733 --> 12:04.833
that was in every way
far more vital

12:04.867 --> 12:06.733
to American security interests

12:06.767 --> 12:08.200
and of far more importance

12:08.233 --> 12:12.500
to global strategic
and economic concerns.

12:12.533 --> 12:16.867
Where we operated
were the frankincense trees.

12:16.900 --> 12:19.500
The frankincense that the Wise
men brought to Christ.

12:19.533 --> 12:21.233
All the sudden,
they came through mountains

12:21.267 --> 12:23.200
where we were fighting.

12:26.833 --> 12:30.200
And you're sitting
behind a machine gun

12:30.233 --> 12:34.400
on a track, which had been used
for 3,00 years.

12:34.433 --> 12:37.100
One felt like an intruder
in history.

12:38.400 --> 12:39.700
And if the trees were cut,

12:39.733 --> 12:43.233
you could smell
the frankincense.

12:43.267 --> 12:47.167
The smell of explosives.

12:47.200 --> 12:50.800
The smell of blood.

12:50.833 --> 12:56.067
The smell of the food.
Cardamom, the smell of the tea.

12:56.100 --> 12:58.100
I loved it.

12:58.133 --> 13:00.200
This was a civil war.

13:00.233 --> 13:03.233
Civil wars, typically,
are the worst wars of all.

13:03.267 --> 13:05.467
I mean, you know that
well enough in your country.

13:05.500 --> 13:07.900
But most people
have not heard of it.

13:07.933 --> 13:10.100
No, they haven't.
But you'd have heard about it

13:10.133 --> 13:13.300
if we'd lost it, I can tell you.
Right.

13:13.333 --> 13:15.300
The war began
as a local rebellion

13:15.333 --> 13:17.733
by the Dhofari people
against the autocratic

13:17.767 --> 13:22.167
and outdated rule of then
Sultan, Said bin Taimur,

13:22.200 --> 13:24.700
who had kept his nation
isolated and stunted

13:24.733 --> 13:27.167
out of his concern
for his hold on power.

13:28.733 --> 13:30.567
What started as a local uprising

13:30.600 --> 13:32.967
quickly became a serious,
full-blown,

13:33.000 --> 13:34.700
communist-backed insurgency,

13:34.733 --> 13:39.133
as Soviet and Chinese influence
poured in through Yemen.

13:42.767 --> 13:45.500
Ian Gardner remembers
the conflict well.

13:45.533 --> 13:48.333
He fought in it,
alongside Omani infantry

13:48.367 --> 13:50.100
as a British Royal Marine.

13:50.133 --> 13:51.633
And later wrote about
the experience

13:51.667 --> 13:54.367
in his memoir,
"In the Service of the Sultan,"

13:54.400 --> 13:57.733
a rare chronicle of the brutal,
incredibly difficult

13:57.767 --> 14:00.467
and almost entirely unknown war,

14:00.500 --> 14:03.000
fought in the rugged
southern mountains.

14:03.033 --> 14:05.533
The old Sultan was not
an inhuman man.

14:05.567 --> 14:08.267
But he was an old man.
He was deeply reactionary.

14:08.300 --> 14:12.467
So he wanted to keep his country
in a medieval time warp.

14:12.500 --> 14:15.467
The thing that changed it
was the advent of

14:15.500 --> 14:17.800
the Japanese transistor radio.

14:17.833 --> 14:20.033
And the first time,
his people could hear

14:20.067 --> 14:22.500
what the other Arab countries
were doing with their oil.

14:22.533 --> 14:25.267
And they wanted some of that.

14:25.300 --> 14:27.733
By the 1920s, Winston
Churchill had switched

14:27.767 --> 14:29.967
the British Royal Navy's
mode of power

14:30.000 --> 14:31.367
from coal to oil.

14:31.400 --> 14:33.767
And suddenly,
everything changed.

14:33.800 --> 14:35.567
They needed oil and lots of it.

14:35.600 --> 14:37.367
Which made Oman vital.

14:37.400 --> 14:39.833
Not for its limited
oil resources,

14:39.867 --> 14:41.467
but for where it is.

14:41.500 --> 14:44.233
The Strait of Hormuz,
the Persian Gulf's

14:44.267 --> 14:45.767
femoral artery.

14:45.800 --> 14:48.367
20% of the world's oil
flows through here,

14:48.400 --> 14:50.867
making it one of... if not the...

14:50.900 --> 14:54.133
Most strategically important
waterways on the planet.

14:54.167 --> 14:56.000
♪

14:57.400 --> 14:59.467
By 1970, Sultan Taimur's

14:59.500 --> 15:02.533
counterinsurgency
was not going well.

15:02.567 --> 15:06.333
He was deposed by his son,
Qaboos bin Said al Said,

15:06.367 --> 15:08.533
in a relatively bloodless coup.

15:08.567 --> 15:10.733
Immediately,
the young Sultan set out

15:10.767 --> 15:13.300
on a different tact
for winning the war.

15:13.333 --> 15:16.333
Longs before
the shooting had stopped,

15:16.367 --> 15:19.167
we would institute
a civil aid program.

15:19.200 --> 15:22.067
Build roads, build a school,
build a mosque,

15:22.100 --> 15:24.467
build some shops, a clinic.

15:24.500 --> 15:26.500
But was in this way
the Sultan was able

15:26.533 --> 15:29.633
to demonstrate
that he was the one

15:29.667 --> 15:32.767
who had his people's best
interests at heart,

15:32.800 --> 15:34.833
not the communists.

15:34.867 --> 15:36.933
Things seldom work out so well

15:36.967 --> 15:39.667
post-insurgency
or counterinsurgency.

15:39.700 --> 15:43.700
This tactic failed spectacularly
in Vietnam, of course.

15:43.733 --> 15:45.800
What made the difference here?

15:45.833 --> 15:48.433
In every war in history,

15:48.467 --> 15:51.367
you end up living
with the other side.

15:51.400 --> 15:56.633
And if you can open
a respectable door successfully,

15:56.667 --> 15:59.400
then the less likely
the aftermath

15:59.433 --> 16:01.400
is gonna be beset with rancor,

16:01.433 --> 16:04.733
with hatred
and a thirst for revenge.

16:04.767 --> 16:08.467
The Sultan took this very brave,

16:08.500 --> 16:11.200
highly intelligent
political risk,

16:11.233 --> 16:13.133
which I think was the
difference.

16:13.167 --> 16:15.433
And I think has been
the foundation

16:15.467 --> 16:21.400
of the unambiguous and enduring
peace in this country.

16:30.867 --> 16:34.367
In 1976, the Omanis
laid down their weapons.

16:34.400 --> 16:37.300
And never picked them up again.

16:37.333 --> 16:41.633
The resulting peace
has lasted for 40 years.

16:41.667 --> 16:44.900
And while Oman ain't your
system, and it ain't my system,

16:44.933 --> 16:47.833
and it's far, far from being
either perfect

16:47.867 --> 16:50.000
or a Western-style democracy,

16:50.033 --> 16:51.667
there is a palpable pride here

16:51.700 --> 16:55.367
in the collective identity
of being Omani.

16:55.400 --> 16:58.933
♪

16:58.967 --> 17:01.833
Notably, as well, the Sultan
has placed emphasis

17:01.867 --> 17:03.300
on the role of women,

17:03.333 --> 17:05.433
decreeing... at least,
as a matter of policy...

17:05.467 --> 17:07.967
Equal access to education,

17:08.000 --> 17:11.900
to work, to political office.

17:14.933 --> 17:15.433
♪

17:50.833 --> 17:52.767
Zahara al-Oufi,

17:52.800 --> 17:55.733
daughters Asilah and Aisha

17:55.767 --> 17:58.100
and friend Samia Alharthy...

17:58.133 --> 18:00.933
Four extraordinary women.

18:00.967 --> 18:04.400
What started as a way for
Zahara to fund her charity work

18:04.433 --> 18:06.767
spawned a lucrative
cottage industry

18:06.800 --> 18:09.100
of catering for events.

18:09.133 --> 18:11.233
Now, rather than using
her family money,

18:11.267 --> 18:13.533
her business is able
to fully finance her work

18:13.567 --> 18:16.767
to educate children in the
nearby mountain villages.

18:20.200 --> 18:23.067
- "The Simpsons."
- Yeah!

18:23.100 --> 18:26.233
I was asking myself,
had I seen "The Simpsons"?

18:26.267 --> 18:28.067
- I was on "The Simpsons."
- Oh yeah?

18:28.100 --> 18:29.100
- Yes.
- Really?

18:29.133 --> 18:30.500
Yes. This is the first time

18:30.533 --> 18:32.333
I've been recognized
from "The Simpsons."

18:32.367 --> 18:34.800
That's really nice.

18:34.833 --> 18:37.133
So, some of the money
that she's making

18:37.167 --> 18:40.033
is going to open schools
in rural villages.

18:40.067 --> 18:43.133
Is that correct?
Not only a part of the money;

18:43.167 --> 18:44.933
it goes all of it for them.

18:44.967 --> 18:46.567
To build, for them, the schools

18:46.600 --> 18:48.800
and to provide them
the education.

19:00.700 --> 19:02.600
Why is this important to you?

19:09.133 --> 19:11.567
Kabuli Laham is slow-cooked goat

19:11.600 --> 19:15.967
in a rich, rice pilaf,
scented with star anise.

19:16.000 --> 19:18.833
Musanif djaj...
A local specialty...

19:18.867 --> 19:21.967
Are pan-seared dumplings,
stuffed with chicken, pepper,

19:22.000 --> 19:24.400
ginger, turmeric, and onions.

19:24.433 --> 19:27.633
And of course,
there's Omani bread with honey.

19:27.667 --> 19:29.800
That's a chili.
Are you okay with that?

19:29.833 --> 19:31.867
Yes. I like spicy.

19:31.900 --> 19:34.567
- Oh! Okay.
- Good. Mmm.

19:34.600 --> 19:39.767
Very good.

19:44.733 --> 19:47.400
Everyone here says
that the economy

19:47.433 --> 19:50.433
is going to have to shift
away from oil

19:50.467 --> 19:52.833
towards other industries.
Yeah.

19:52.867 --> 19:56.633
How would you like to
prepare your daughters

19:56.667 --> 19:58.700
for the future?

20:27.800 --> 20:31.433
What do the young ladies,
when they reach adulthood,

20:31.467 --> 20:33.367
what are your hopes and dreams?

20:47.467 --> 20:49.100
And the other...
The young lady?

21:01.500 --> 21:03.033
Ah, strong women in this family.

21:03.067 --> 21:05.267
Yeah.

21:05.300 --> 21:08.067
Very strong ones.

21:11.100 --> 21:11.600
♪

21:50.633 --> 21:53.900
As one moves away from the
coast and into the interior,

21:53.933 --> 21:55.667
everything changes.

21:57.767 --> 22:00.733
This is the country's
more conservative core;

22:00.767 --> 22:03.400
its spiritual center.

22:09.600 --> 22:13.800
Uniquely, Oman's majority
is neither Sunni or Shia,

22:13.833 --> 22:15.500
but rather, Ibadi,

22:15.533 --> 22:17.500
a very old
and particularly tolerant

22:17.533 --> 22:21.133
non-sectarian form of Islam.

22:21.167 --> 22:25.400
This is a distinction we in the
West would be wise to notice.

22:25.433 --> 22:27.733
Islam is not a monolith.

22:27.767 --> 22:30.133
It comes in many forms.

22:35.733 --> 22:38.633
Ibadi theology arguable forms
the backbone

22:38.667 --> 22:41.333
of many of Oman's
codes of conduct.

22:41.367 --> 22:44.367
It places value on concepts
like politeness,

22:44.400 --> 22:48.800
acceptance,
unity, and understanding.

22:58.233 --> 23:00.133
Perhaps as
a consequence of that,

23:00.167 --> 23:02.867
the sultanate embraces
grace and tact

23:02.900 --> 23:05.367
as a matter of foreign policy.

23:05.400 --> 23:08.200
Internally, too,
Oman has avoided radicalism

23:08.233 --> 23:09.767
and sectarian violence.

23:09.800 --> 23:12.600
It is considered shameful,
by Ibadi teachings,

23:12.633 --> 23:15.133
to draw blood
over religious conflicts,

23:15.167 --> 23:17.367
unless attacked.

23:17.400 --> 23:20.033
The terror and bloodshed
in neighboring Yemen

23:20.067 --> 23:22.800
feel very far away up here.

23:22.833 --> 23:26.100
Jabal Al Akhdar,
the Green Mountain.

23:29.000 --> 23:30.467
This area... oh, my God, it's...

23:30.500 --> 23:32.533
Look at this, it's so beautiful.
Yeah.

23:32.567 --> 23:35.000
There are 64 villages
at Jebel Al Akhdar.

23:35.033 --> 23:36.433
- 64?
- 64.

23:36.467 --> 23:38.233
And this place is going;
they are dying.

23:38.267 --> 23:41.033
How many generations
has your family lived here?

23:41.067 --> 23:43.200
- 200 years, maybe. Maybe more.
- 200 years.

23:43.233 --> 23:44.233
- Yeah.
- More than.

23:44.267 --> 23:45.600
More than 200 years.

23:45.633 --> 23:47.533
Can you see
all the small famers?

23:47.567 --> 23:49.900
- Yeah.
- All of our grandfathers

23:49.933 --> 23:51.400
built that.

23:51.433 --> 23:53.300
And they built all these things

23:53.333 --> 23:55.300
with only their hands.

23:55.333 --> 23:56.733
They didn't have any machines.

23:56.767 --> 23:58.000
Can you imagine that?

24:01.033 --> 24:01.533
♪

24:06.133 --> 24:08.567
Hamdan Al Saqri, his father Ali

24:08.600 --> 24:11.300
and his uncle Hilal
come from a very long line

24:11.333 --> 24:13.367
of hard-working farmers.

24:13.400 --> 24:17.233
They all grew up here,
generation after generation.

24:17.267 --> 24:19.267
A tribal area of ancient
villages

24:19.300 --> 24:21.333
and terraced farm land,
which have produced

24:21.367 --> 24:23.633
pomegranate, nuts, and dates...

24:23.667 --> 24:26.000
The premier cash crops of Oman...

24:26.033 --> 24:27.900
For many centuries.

24:27.933 --> 24:29.600
But like so many places I go...

24:29.633 --> 24:32.400
So many traditional
agricultural communities...

24:32.433 --> 24:35.067
The young men... and increasingly
the young women...

24:35.100 --> 24:37.567
Are looking elsewhere,
beyond the farm

24:37.600 --> 24:41.667
to seek higher education
and opportunity in the city.

24:41.700 --> 24:44.633
This is a common story.
I mean, the young men,

24:44.667 --> 24:46.833
they go to university,
you know...

24:46.867 --> 24:50.033
I have to study there
because, you know, the future

24:50.067 --> 24:52.633
and I want to get a good job.

24:52.667 --> 24:54.633
Many young Omanis,
they study abroad,

24:54.667 --> 24:56.433
they study
in America or England.

24:56.467 --> 24:58.167
But most of them
seem to come back.

24:58.200 --> 25:00.433
Mm. You are only going outside

25:00.467 --> 25:02.233
to study and get something.

25:02.267 --> 25:05.067
That thing, you want to return
back to your country.

25:05.100 --> 25:07.500
I grown up in this village.

25:07.533 --> 25:10.600
It's something simple
and I really miss it.

25:10.633 --> 25:12.467
- Muscat, you don't like it?
- Sometimes.

25:12.500 --> 25:13.826
- It's not a life for you?
- Sometimes?

25:13.833 --> 25:19.167
Sometimes you go there
for big shop... malls.

25:19.200 --> 25:20.867
You go to the malls.

25:20.900 --> 25:23.067
Yeah, I like to sometimes.

25:23.100 --> 25:26.133
- So what do we have here?
- We have food.

25:26.167 --> 25:27.233
It's delicious.

25:27.267 --> 25:30.967
- Delicious. All right.
- Yeah.

25:31.000 --> 25:32.800
Oh, man. That looks good.

25:32.833 --> 25:35.867
What's in the biryani?
This is rice and potato.

25:35.900 --> 25:38.300
- Potato?
- Yeah.

25:38.333 --> 25:41.133
We often eat this meat
at celebrations.

25:41.167 --> 25:43.600
We call it
[speaks native language].

25:43.633 --> 25:44.933
- Lamb?
- Yeah.

25:44.967 --> 25:46.433
Mmm. Oh, that's fantastic.

25:46.467 --> 25:47.867
- You like?
- Wow.

25:47.900 --> 25:49.667
Never had this.
Really?

25:49.700 --> 25:52.100
This is the harees.
Very famous dish.

25:52.133 --> 25:53.933
- Yeah, yeah.
- How do you say "delicious"

25:53.967 --> 25:55.600
in Arabic?
Ladhidh.

25:55.633 --> 25:56.867
- Ladhidh?
- Ladhidh, yeah.

25:56.900 --> 25:58.267
- Ooh.
- Ladhidh.

25:58.300 --> 26:00.067
That's what it is.

26:00.100 --> 26:02.067
How did you learn
to cook this well?

26:02.100 --> 26:03.700
In Muscat,
I lived with my friends.

26:03.733 --> 26:05.367
- Mm-hmm.
- I'm not trained from it.

26:05.400 --> 26:06.933
So I have to learn how to cook

26:06.967 --> 26:09.433
because no one
is taking care about you.

26:09.467 --> 26:13.500
You should care about yourself.

26:13.533 --> 26:16.400
So if you'd rather be here,
why not just continue

26:16.433 --> 26:18.267
as your parents
and your grandparents?

26:18.300 --> 26:22.467
Mm, I want to really improve
my country economy.

26:22.500 --> 26:25.367
I want to invent something.
You're planning

26:25.400 --> 26:28.300
for a post-oil Oman.
Yeah.

26:28.333 --> 26:29.700
Like, after the oil

26:29.733 --> 26:31.272
I think the whole country
feels this way.

26:31.300 --> 26:34.667
I mean, the government
feels this way as well.

26:34.700 --> 26:36.533
As you say,
the country is changing.

26:36.567 --> 26:38.800
You have a luxury resort
right over there.

26:38.833 --> 26:40.067
- Yeah.
- The future will

26:40.100 --> 26:42.033
look much like this.

26:42.067 --> 26:45.267
Resort opens up.
The have a big golf course,

26:45.300 --> 26:48.200
they have jobs for people
to carry golf bags for tourists.

26:48.233 --> 26:49.867
- Yeah.
- For more money than he could

26:49.900 --> 26:51.200
make farming.

26:51.233 --> 26:52.967
Is this good or is this bad?

26:53.000 --> 26:56.567
You have to deal with your
traditional way and your life.

26:56.600 --> 27:00.667
So you want to keep
all things safe.

27:00.700 --> 27:03.300
It's more the
government responsibility.

27:03.333 --> 27:05.600
To make balance
between advantages

27:05.633 --> 27:08.567
and disadvantages of tourism.

27:08.600 --> 27:10.300
But it's a very delicate
balance here

27:10.333 --> 27:13.200
These are old and complicated
systems that have been

27:13.233 --> 27:15.933
working for a very long time.

27:15.967 --> 27:18.767
It's really difficult because
there is many sides here.

27:18.800 --> 27:20.300
Life is keep changing.

27:20.333 --> 27:21.367
We cannot keep everything

27:21.400 --> 27:23.533
as it is before.

27:23.567 --> 27:24.967
Do you know this cat
or just a...

27:25.000 --> 27:26.200
- No.
- Just a village cat?

27:26.233 --> 27:27.667
Yeah.

27:27.700 --> 27:29.567
- It's the guard for us.
- It's the guard?

27:29.600 --> 27:32.067
Yeah.

27:35.100 --> 27:35.600
♪

28:12.067 --> 28:13.467
Oman's history and future

28:13.500 --> 28:16.967
both are linked inexorably
to the sea.

28:17.000 --> 28:18.900
The sultanate began with trade.

28:18.933 --> 28:21.833
And it is likely that a new,
multi-billion dollar port...

28:21.867 --> 28:24.500
At Duqm, on the coast...
Intended as a center

28:24.533 --> 28:26.300
for international shipping,

28:26.333 --> 28:29.233
will play a significant role
in the coming years.

28:35.667 --> 28:36.167
♪

29:05.500 --> 29:06.000
♪

29:11.833 --> 29:15.100
Omar Abdullah al-Gilani
and Mohammad Shaban

29:15.133 --> 29:17.300
spend every free moment at sea,

29:17.333 --> 29:20.433
free diving and spear fishing...
Without oxygen...

29:20.467 --> 29:24.033
For grouper, king fish,
cuttlefish, and tuna.

29:26.867 --> 29:30.767
Said al-Naamani is the captain
and owner of this boat.

29:30.800 --> 29:34.200
Saleh Said Al Jabri
is a former Navy officer

29:34.233 --> 29:35.867
who famously sailed a hand-made

29:35.900 --> 29:40.300
ninth century-style dhow
3,000 miles to Singapore.

29:43.333 --> 29:44.633
The fist Omani boats

29:44.667 --> 29:47.167
that went out to sea
around how far back?

29:47.200 --> 29:48.433
How many years?

29:48.467 --> 29:50.933
I would say more than
3,000 years.

29:50.967 --> 29:52.667
- So B.C.?
- B.C., yeah.

29:52.700 --> 29:54.267
Now, in the beginning
it was fishermen.

29:54.300 --> 29:56.633
- Yeah.
- But then, start to trade

29:56.667 --> 29:59.433
all up and down East Africa,
Iran, Pakistan,

29:59.467 --> 30:01.767
up the China Straits to China.
Yeah.

30:01.800 --> 30:06.167
And the evidence about it,
even in their China language,

30:06.200 --> 30:08.300
there's some Arabic.
Interesting.

30:08.333 --> 30:10.233
- It's very interesting.
- What did the Chinese

30:10.267 --> 30:13.200
have to trade
that the Omanis wanted?

30:13.233 --> 30:15.300
They exchange it
with the silk fabric

30:15.333 --> 30:16.733
and all the kind of things.

30:16.767 --> 30:19.033
And of course, coming back
was spices.

30:19.067 --> 30:22.333
Not only Arabs went,
the Indians comes as well.

30:22.367 --> 30:26.067
So if you look at
the eastern coast,

30:26.100 --> 30:30.633
they like the spices and all
this kind of food.

30:30.667 --> 30:32.367
Well, the people also.
I mean, you know,

30:32.400 --> 30:38.300
it's a real mix of Arab,
southern Indian, African.

30:38.333 --> 30:40.333
I mean, maybe that's why
the food's so delicious.

30:40.367 --> 30:42.333
This food is so delicious

30:42.367 --> 30:44.067
because we like the taste.

30:49.467 --> 30:49.967
♪

30:55.567 --> 30:59.067
Lunch is fresh sardines
grilled over charcoal...

31:01.100 --> 31:03.367
some incredible prawns...

31:07.700 --> 31:11.067
And mishkak,
an Omani cookout staple.

31:11.100 --> 31:13.233
Cubed beef on skewers,
rubbed with cumin,

31:13.267 --> 31:16.800
garlic, and cardamom,
then grilled.

31:16.833 --> 31:19.667
And local slipper lobsters,
of course.

31:19.700 --> 31:21.633
♪

31:21.667 --> 31:24.833
And do not forget
the cuttlefish masala.

31:24.867 --> 31:28.400
♪

31:28.433 --> 31:30.800
Delicious. Wow,
that cuttlefish is incredible.

31:30.833 --> 31:33.533
♪

31:33.567 --> 31:36.100
We cannot live without the sea.

31:36.133 --> 31:40.433
Our relationship with the sea
is too strong.

31:40.467 --> 31:42.300
So you go in the water
every day?

31:42.333 --> 31:45.167
Myself, I like
being in the water.

31:45.200 --> 31:47.900
Even 24 hours I don't mind.

31:50.933 --> 31:51.433
♪

31:55.167 --> 31:58.567
This is what's great
about Oman itself.

31:58.600 --> 32:02.167
People cannot go away
from the sea itself.

32:02.200 --> 32:05.233
From the sand itself.

32:05.267 --> 32:07.133
What we like is, like, nature.

32:07.167 --> 32:11.467
We want to make it
as natural as it looks

32:11.500 --> 32:15.200
and it appears
and how it was before.

32:15.233 --> 32:18.500
We born in
this beautiful country

32:18.533 --> 32:22.367
and we try to look after it.

32:22.400 --> 32:25.700
It have to stay good,
inside the heart, here.

32:25.733 --> 32:27.533
It's like the flower.

32:27.567 --> 32:30.200
If we keep it and look after it,

32:30.233 --> 32:33.033
give them the right water,
it will grow.

32:33.067 --> 32:33.567
♪

32:50.467 --> 32:50.967
♪

33:02.567 --> 33:03.067
♪

33:15.500 --> 33:19.233
130 miles south of Muscat,

33:19.267 --> 33:22.033
the pavement ends
and you hit this.

33:22.067 --> 33:24.633
♪

33:24.667 --> 33:30.367
Sharqiya Sands,
on the edge of Rub' al Khali,

33:30.400 --> 33:33.433
the largest sand desert
in the world.

33:33.467 --> 33:37.333
♪

33:37.367 --> 33:41.733
Once you get up in a soft sand,
things change.

33:41.767 --> 33:44.133
Everything changes.

33:44.167 --> 33:45.500
You change.

33:54.933 --> 33:55.433
♪

34:01.567 --> 34:04.467
This is the traditional
domain of the Bedouin.

34:07.000 --> 34:08.333
Who, for thousands of years,

34:08.367 --> 34:10.733
have moved across
this harsh, dry,

34:10.766 --> 34:14.433
seemingly endless landscape,
making it their home.

34:17.632 --> 34:22.667
Amir Al Wahabi and his family
continue the tradition.

34:22.699 --> 34:25.933
Ahmed Al-Naroudi
is a hardcore ambassador

34:25.967 --> 34:27.933
for the empty places
of the desert.

34:27.967 --> 34:30.800
He's spent more time there,
much of it alone,

34:30.833 --> 34:33.167
than just about anyone.

34:33.199 --> 34:35.567
The Bedouin have been crossing
the Empty Quarter

34:35.600 --> 34:36.699
hundreds of years?

34:36.733 --> 34:38.266
Thousands of years?
Thousand of years.

34:38.300 --> 34:39.766
Thousand of years.

34:39.800 --> 34:42.900
The Bedouin are the kings
of the desert.

34:42.933 --> 34:46.300
It's their place.
It's their area.

34:46.333 --> 34:49.199
And they know how to live
and they know how to survive.

34:55.400 --> 34:57.833
Mark Evans... a polar
and desert expedition leader...

34:57.867 --> 35:01.400
Knows firsthand how difficult
the Empty Quarter can be.

35:01.433 --> 35:03.200
Guided by Amir, and accompanied

35:03.233 --> 35:05.867
by Khalid Mohammad Al-Zadjali,

35:05.900 --> 35:07.400
he recently made the crossing,

35:07.433 --> 35:11.967
walking over 600 miles
with camels in tow.

35:12.000 --> 35:13.633
The first 12 days
of our journey,

35:13.667 --> 35:15.260
crossing the Empty quarter,
we didn't touch

35:15.267 --> 35:16.767
our own food at all.

35:16.800 --> 35:18.767
And it became a competition
to become more generous

35:18.800 --> 35:20.867
than the previous...
So you need people out there,

35:20.900 --> 35:22.067
all along the way.
You would.

35:22.100 --> 35:23.300
Even though nobody lived there,

35:23.333 --> 35:24.967
people would find you
and travel.

35:33.167 --> 35:33.667
♪

35:50.600 --> 35:51.100
♪

36:14.600 --> 36:17.800
Usually, the guy who come,
he have to open the head.

36:17.833 --> 36:19.967
Okay. Oh, I know just
what I'm going for.

36:20.000 --> 36:21.500
I got it.
Pull it.

36:21.533 --> 36:23.367
Yeah, that is all.
Cheek.

36:23.400 --> 36:25.933
Yeah.
Remove the eyes.

36:25.967 --> 36:27.100
Here.
Ooh, ooh.

36:27.133 --> 36:31.067
It's too hot.

36:31.100 --> 36:33.467
This is the part.
Mmm. Good.

36:33.500 --> 36:36.433
It's good if have got whiskey,
or brandy or...

36:38.900 --> 36:40.993
You know, the Empty Quarter
is emptier than it's ever been.

36:41.000 --> 36:44.300
It's almost impossible to do
what the old explorers did

36:44.333 --> 36:47.900
because they relied upon
local people being in sit...

36:47.933 --> 36:51.033
The Bedouin have migrated
to the edge of the deserts,

36:51.067 --> 36:52.800
where life is easier, really.

36:52.833 --> 36:55.567
But they don't want to
let go completely.

36:55.600 --> 36:58.367
Amir sends his children
to school in Bidiya.

36:58.400 --> 37:00.633
But yet, he wants them to live
in the sand,

37:00.667 --> 37:02.967
where they have the freedom
and that connection

37:03.000 --> 37:04.333
to their roots.

37:12.133 --> 37:12.633
♪

37:28.700 --> 37:29.200
♪

38:48.033 --> 38:48.533
♪

38:55.600 --> 38:57.433
Does someone cross
the Empty Quarter alone?

38:57.467 --> 39:00.967
Absolutely alone?
No, you need people with you.

39:01.000 --> 39:02.933
You need people.

39:02.967 --> 39:05.333
In my earlier years, I was
taking lots of young people

39:05.367 --> 39:07.333
on expeditions up to the Arctic,

39:07.367 --> 39:08.393
which is very different to here.

39:08.400 --> 39:10.467
But the Inuit and the Bedouin

39:10.500 --> 39:12.300
have a lot of similarities.

39:14.833 --> 39:18.200
They both live on the edge
of human tolerance.

39:21.200 --> 39:24.267
They're much more open
and friendly people.

39:27.500 --> 39:28.000
♪

39:44.667 --> 39:45.167
♪

40:21.000 --> 40:21.500
♪

40:53.900 --> 40:55.867
It's like coming home
when you come out here.

40:55.900 --> 40:58.267
It's very incredibly powerful

40:58.300 --> 41:01.000
and enables you to put
everything in perspective.

41:03.467 --> 41:05.367
Fridtjof Nansen,
a Norwegian explorer

41:05.400 --> 41:08.233
said that salvation
will not come from

41:08.267 --> 41:10.400
the rushing centers
of civilization.

41:10.433 --> 41:15.267
Deliverance will come
from the lonely places.

41:15.300 --> 41:17.000
In other words,
we all need places to think

41:17.033 --> 41:18.667
and calm down and...

41:32.833 --> 41:33.333
♪

